```latex
\section{Timely-RL}

After proposing Timely-Eval, we argue that the awareness of time is a capability that should and can be reinforced during training. Since latency fluctuations provide dynamic and real-time feedback, Reinforcement Learning is well-suited to calibrate this capability in models. Therefore, we design Timely-RL, a time-aware multi-turn interactive reinforcement learning algorithm.

First, during the RL process, the time feedback $t^{(i)}$ obtained by the model at the $i$-th interaction step is computed as the sum of the model inference time $t_{\text{gen}}^{(i)}$ and the tool execution time $t_{\text{tool}}^{(i)}$. Here, the actual value of $t_{\text{gen}}^{(i)}$ is determined by the hardware resources during training. To enable the model to adapt to inference under different conditions, we multiply $t_{\text{gen}}^{(i)}$ by a coefficient $\alpha$ as the actual feedback received by the model, simulating the actual inference scenarios on faster or slower devices. Meanwhile, we deploy the tools on a server with fixed hardware resources to ensure stability in tool invocation feedback speed.

Next, we design corresponding reward functions for the three tasks and mix them for RL training. For any response, let $r_{\text{acc}}$ denote the accuracy reward, $t$ denote the time cost for task completion, and $T_{\text{max}}$ denote the time limit. The reward function for the three tasks can be uniformly expressed as:
\begin{equation}
R(t, r_{\text{acc}}) = 
\begin{cases}
0, & \text{if } t > T_{\text{max}} \\
r_{\text{format}}, & \text{if } t \le T_{\text{max}} \land r_{\text{acc}} = 0 \\
r_{\text{format}} + r_{\text{acc}} + \lambda \cdot U(t, T_{\text{max}}), & \text{if } t \le T_{\text{max}} \land r_{\text{acc}} > 0
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
where $r_{\text{format}}$ is a fixed reward for correct formatting and timely completion, and $U(t, T_{\text{max}})$ represents the model's utilization rate of time cost, calculated as:
\begin{equation}
U(t, T_{\text{max}}) = \sin\left( \frac{\pi}{2} \cdot \min\left(\frac{t}{T_{\text{max}}}, 1\right) \right)
\end{equation}
This mapping ensures that as the time ratio approaches 1.0, the reward gradually plateaus and eventually saturates, thereby mitigating the impact of minor time fluctuations near the deadline and making training more stable.
